ExecDesc: Microsoft IIS WebDAV Request Directory Security Bypass
EngDesc: A security bypass vulnerability exists in the Microsoft Internet Information Services (IIS) WebDAV. The vulnerability is due to the way IIS handles WebDAV requests for directories requiring authentication. A remote attacker can exploit the vulnerability to bypass access restrictions on WebDAV server. A successful attack attempt will allow the attacker to bypass security controls, upload or download arbitrary files to protected WebDAV folders.

ExecDesc: Microsoft IIS Directory Authentication Security Bypass
EngDesc:
A policy bypass vulnerability exists in Microsoft Internet Information Services. The vulnerability is due to an error while processing HTTP requests for resources protected by access control mechanisms. If the protected directory resides on a NTFS file system, and the NTFS name and stream type are included in the directory name in an HTTP request, then information in protected directories can be accessed without authentication.
Remote unauthenticated attackers can exploit this vulnerability by sending specially crafted HTTP requests to a vulnerable Microsoft IIS server. Successful exploitation would allow the attacker to bypass security checks to list, and download files from a vulnerable system.

ExecDesc: Microsoft IIS PROPFIND MS04-030 Denial of Service
EngDesc: This threat causes Microsoft IIS server versions 5.0 and 6.0 to eat up a large amount of CPU and memory resources, causing a denial of service.  This is caused by sending it a specifically crafted XML message which causes the parser to spend a long period of time dissecting it.

ExecDesc: IIS TRACK Request
EngDesc: IIS 5.0 has an undocumented HTTP request TRACK.  This request operates the same way as the RFC compliant request, TRACE.  TRACK can be used for cross-site scripting attacks and password theft, and unlike TRACE it is not logged by IIS.  IIS is a webserver, and typically listens on port 80.

ExecDesc: ASP Data Stream Source Disclosure
EngDesc: This threat causes a webserver to deliver the source code to a file instead of executing it.  This is performed by using the little known ::$DATA stream ability of the NTFS file system.  This threat performs a GET request for default.asp::$DATA.  Webservers typically listen on port 80.

ExecDesc: HTTP GET localhost Error Page Request
EngDesc: This threat issues a HTTP request for the localhost host.  This can disclose more details in scripting errors, allowing for attacker to discover the exact nature of a web script's failure.  This is caused by a built in error reporting feature of IIS 5 and 6.  IIS is a webserver, and typically listens on port 80.

ExecDesc: MS00-094 IIS Phone Book Server Buffer Overrun
EngDesc: This threat takes advantage of a buffer overflow in the phone book service of IIS 4.0 and 5.0.  Causes remote code to be executed listing a directory listing in winnt\system32.

ExecDesc: IIS .printer Request Buffer Overflow
EngDesc: This threat is a buffer overflow request that affects IIS 5.0 for Windows 2000 with Service Pack 1 or previous installed.  It takes advantage of a flaw in the .printer directive for this version of IIS.

ExecDesc: IIS Source Code Disclosure Unicode
EngDesc: By sending a Translate: f header element, sending a portion of the request in Unicode, and having the target website run on a FAT32 partition, it is possible to read the source code of an ASP based website.  This allows a remote attacker to read files that store database access information, and examine code for storing and reading cookies.  IIS is a webserver, and typically listens on port 80.
